Hierarchical Gaussian process regression with application to microarray data

Spencer Woody

August 26, 2017

Introduction

Based on a paper by Hensman, Lawrence, and Rattray, we model gene expression levels as a hierarchical Gaussian process,

\[ \begin{aligned} h_i(t) &\sim \text{GP}(\mathbf{0}, k_h(t, t')) \\ g_n(t) &\sim \text{GP}(h_i(t), k_g(t, t')) \text{ for } n\in c_i \\ f_{nr}(t) &\sim \text{GP}(g_n(t), k_f(t, t')). \end{aligned} \]

library(tidyverse)
library(RColorBrewer)
theme_set(theme_bw(base_size = 12)) # Slightly larger text for ggplot2

# Read in data, rearrange columns & rows, change levels order in gene factor
drosophila <- read_csv("droslong.csv") %>%
    select(group, gene, replicate, time, log2exp) %>% 
    arrange(group, gene, replicate, time) %>% 
    mutate(gene = fct_inorder(gene))

Including Plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

allgenes <- drosophila %>% 
    ggplot(aes(time, log2exp)) +
    geom_point(aes(col = group, alpha = replicate)) +
    facet_wrap(~gene) +
    labs(title = "Expression Profiles for all Genes",
         x = "Time",
         y = "log2-Normalized gene expression") + 
    scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Dark2") +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 12, by = 2)) 
allgenes

group1plot <- drosophila %>% 
    filter(group == "group1") %>% 
    ggplot(aes(time, log2exp)) +
    geom_point(aes(col = gene)) +
    facet_wrap(~gene) +
    labs(title = "Expression Profiles for all Genes",
         x = "Time",
         y = "log2-Normalized gene expression") + 
    scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 12, by = 2)) +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(drosophila$log2exp),
                                  max(drosophila$log2exp)))

group2plot <- drosophila %>% 
    filter(group == "group2") %>% 
    ggplot(aes(time, log2exp)) +
    geom_point(aes(col = gene)) +
    facet_wrap(~gene) +
    labs(title = "Expression Profiles for all Genes",
         x = "Time",
         y = "log2-Normalized gene expression") + 
    scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 12, by = 2)) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(min(drosophila$log2exp),
                                  max(drosophila$log2exp)))

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.
